# UI Control Style Guide

All form controls share one canonical style defined in `static/style.css`. Never
re-implement control styling inline or borrow an unrelated class. Reusing these
classes is what keeps every screen looking the same.

## Buttons / links

Use `.btn` on `<button>` and `<a>` only. Variants: `.btn.accent`, `.btn.danger`,
`.btn.sm`, `.btn.icon-btn`.

```js
el("button", { class: "btn accent", html: `${icon("plus")} Add` });
```

## Inputs, selects, textareas

Two equivalent ways to get the canonical look — pick one, never style raw:

1. Wrap in a `.field` (preferred in static HTML modals): the inner
   `<input>/<select>/<textarea>` is styled automatically.
2. Add the `.control` class directly (preferred for JS-created standalone
   controls). Add `.sm` for the compact variant.

```js
// ✅ GOOD — canonical select
el("select", { class: "control sm" });
el("input", { class: "control sm", type: "number" });

// ❌ BAD — a select wearing a button class (no caret, no focus ring)
el("select", { class: "btn sm" });

// ❌ BAD — bare control, inherits no styling
el("input", { type: "number" });
```

`.lang-select` is a legacy alias kept only for the topbar language picker; do not
use it for new controls — use `.control`.

## Checkboxes

Custom checkbox styling applies inside `.field.checkbox` / `.lib-check`, or via
`.control` on the checkbox itself.

```js
el("input", { class: "control", type: "checkbox" }); // ✅
el("input", { type: "checkbox" });                    // ❌ unstyled box
```

## Rules

- Never put `.btn` on a `<select>`, `<input>`, or `<textarea>`.
- Never add inline/duplicate CSS for a control that `.control` already covers.
- If you need a new control variant, extend the canonical `.control` rules in
  `static/style.css` rather than creating a one-off class.
